			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I think Greenspan's idea of incorporating some sort of national sales tax</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I dont really like the idea of anything other than an income tax because they're to easy to hide.  How many pepole know what % of the price ofa gallon of gas is actually taxes?  Sort of like toll roads.  Sometimes the toll goes up 25 cents but we really dont attribute this to a raise in taxes, which is exactly what it is.  
<br />

<br />
Austin, my home town, is a good example of toll roads and how they are being used to raise taxes.
<br />

<br />
As I understand it, the premise behind a toll road is that basically the people of the city who use the road are paying for its construction.  Thats how the city of Austin has been "selling" the idea to the people of Austin.  You don't HAVE to use the toll roads.  There are options to go around them, but they'll be the best route for North-South traffic through central and eastern Austin.  Most people, especially comuters looking to avoid the disaster that is I-35 will take the toll road.
<br />

<br />
The toll roads are being built and an INCREDIBLE rate.  A year ago they were blueprints.  Today they are almost done.  We're talking major freeways that span the length of a large, metorpolitan city with a population of about 1.25 million.  By comparison, a East-West major highway (290) began construction through Austin in the mid 80's.  Its still not done.
<br />

<br />
Now, not only is the City of Austin building new toll roads, they want to establish tolls on EXISTING roads.  People that is just another tax.  You're not using the funds of the populace to create the roads because they're already there.  
<br />

<br />
The point is, this is how taxes get hidden.  Elected officials get away with raising hidden taxes all the time without the tax payers really knowing about it unless they're paying close attention.  Its why I'm opposed to any tax that I can't easily see, and the most easily seen is an income tax.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
